## Specific Command Patterns

### File Operations
```batch
@echo off
echo Starting file operation...
copy source destination
IF %ERRORLEVEL% EQU 0 (
    echo File operation completed successfully
) ELSE (
    echo File operation failed with error %ERRORLEVEL%
)
```

### WordPress Plugin Installation
```batch
@echo off
echo === Starting WordPress Plugin Installation ===
echo [1/4] Creating plugin directory...
mkdir plugin_dir
echo [2/4] Copying plugin files...
xcopy source destination /E /I /Y
echo [3/4] Setting permissions...
attrib -R destination\*.* /S
echo [4/4] Installation complete!
echo =======================================
echo Plugin installed successfully. Please activate in WordPress admin.
```

### Test Result Verification
```powershell
$result = Measure-Command { Your-Command }
Write-Output "Command completed in $($result.TotalSeconds) seconds"
```

## Specific Command Examples & Workarounds

*   **Behat (wp-env)**: `npx wp-env run tests-cli bash -c "cd /var/www/html/wp-content/themes/austin-shows-theme && /var/www/html/vendor/bin/behat --format=progress --stop-on-failure features/theme/"` (Using `sh` instead of `bash` might help with pathing issues).
*   **PHPUnit (Direct)**: `php vendor/bin/phpunit [path/to/test.php or directory]`
*   **Windows PowerShell Wrappers**: For reliable execution of Docker commands on Windows, use PowerShell wrappers (e.g., `powershell.exe -Command "docker exec <container_id> php /var/www/html/vendor/bin/phpunit ..."`). Apply this to all Docker commands on Windows.
*   **Direct Docker Shell Access**: If commands fail unpredictably within Docker, especially on Windows, use direct shell access for diagnosis: `docker exec -it <container_id> sh` or `docker exec -it <container_id> bash`.

## Implementation Notes

These guidelines are designed to improve command execution visibility and reliability within the Cursor IDE. By following these patterns, the system will provide clearer feedback on command progress and completion status. 




**Remember the mandatory three-space prefix for all `run_terminal_cmd` calls.** 